recordedBy: L. Weldon|M. Sawey|J. Lingan|K. Amato|M. Dezendorf
occurrenceRemarks: Common name: Texas Red Oak, Spanish Oak.
habitat: Open, elongated E-W narrow band of grassland. Dominated by Iva angustifolia and Muhlenbergia reverchonii with occasional annual forbs. Distinct N and S delineated boundaries characterized by Schizachyrium scoparium, Yucca pallida, Quercus buckleyi, and Fraxinus texensis. Pale clay derived from Walnut Marl.
locality: FW Nature Center and Refuge. West Fork of Trinity River watershed. 165 m N, 200 m E (map distances) of junction of Buffalo Road with Hwy. 199 access road at Refuge entrance. From fee collection booth, go 85 m on ESE bearing (111°), then 117 m on E bearing

occurrenceRemarks: Common name: Texas Red Oak.
habitat: Lowest terrace overlooking dry creek bed characterized by walnut limestone. Pocket of prairie dominated by herbaceous grasses and annual forbs; surrounded by a post oak savanna system. Young specimen found surrounded by Indian grass (Sorghastrum nutans).
locality: Outside of Fort Worth. Highway 820 and Jacksboro Highway. Fort Worth Nature Center & Reserve. NE of Gatehouse. 'Riparian' site.
